<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="502" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[246,1080,364,945]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[272,386,524,545]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[396,538,524,545]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Lyreus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alleni">
<emphasis box="[396,538,524,545]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Lyreus alleni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognized among North American colydiines (= 
<taxonomicName box="[358,473,551,572]" class="Insecta" family="Colydiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Colydiidae</taxonomicName>
of authors) by the characteristic sculpture (
<figureCitation box="[938,1000,551,572]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[272,306,1483,1502]" captionTargetBox="[255,1078,266,1459]" captionTargetId="figure-11@2.[252,1079,265,1462]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. habitus." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), complete absence of eyes (
<figureCitation box="[496,563,577,598]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and small size. The narrower form, distinctly shaped pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[446,511,604,625]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and the more parallel­sided prosternal process (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) will distinguished it from the European 
<emphasis box="[709,883,631,652]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aube" authorityYear="1861" box="[709,879,631,652]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Lyreus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subterraneus">L. subterraneus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
with its distinctly broader form, more laterally arcuate pronotum (Fig. 5) and more triangular prosternal process (Fig. 6). The Sardinian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fancello &amp; Leo" authorityYear="1991" box="[706,888,684,705]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Lyreus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septemstriatus">
<emphasis box="[706,888,684,705]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">L. septemstriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs obviously in having only 7 punctured striae, but also in the greatly bisinuate posterior margin of the prontum, which results in a posterior directed median lobe that is received in an excavation in the anterior edge of the elytra (
<figureCitation box="[932,1007,764,785]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[272,306,1483,1502]" captionTargetBox="[255,1078,266,1459]" captionTargetId="figure-11@2.[252,1079,265,1462]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. habitus." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" unit="in" value="3.0">
<figureCitation box="[1065,1078,764,785]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">3</figureCitation>
in
</quantity>
Fancello and Leo 1991). The male genitalia will readily distinguish the species, the parameres of 
<taxonomicName box="[522,612,818,839]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Lyreus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alleni">
<emphasis box="[522,612,818,839]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">L. alleni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[627,692,817,838]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) being blunt and relatively short (in relation to the basal piece and median lobe), while those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aube" authorityYear="1861" box="[910,1078,844,865]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Lyreus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subterraneus">
<emphasis box="[910,1078,844,865]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">L. subterraneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 7) are relatively longer and narrowly acute. The genitalia of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fancello &amp; Leo" authorityYear="1991" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Lyreus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septemstriatus">L. septemstriatus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as illustrated by 
<figureCitation box="[512,600,897,918]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Figure 2</figureCitation>
of Fancello and Leo (1991) are very distinct, with reduced parameres that end in acuminate points.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="502" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[246,1079,963,1582]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[269,390,963,982]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Description.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[467,581,963,982]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" unit="mm" value="2.45" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="2.2">2.2–2.7 mm</quantity>
. Color uniform dark reddish brown. Dorsally covered in large flattened, subcontiguous tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[659,714,987,1006]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[272,306,1483,1502]" captionTargetBox="[255,1078,266,1459]" captionTargetId="figure-11@2.[252,1079,265,1462]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. habitus." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), each bearing a single subdecumbent seta; cuticle smooth and shining on tubercles, dull between, obscured with dirt­encrusted secretions. 
<emphasis box="[353,403,1035,1054]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Head</emphasis>
somewhat pentagonal (
<figureCitation box="[633,692,1035,1054]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), covered with large flattened tubercles, the largest starting in a broad median band on the occiput, and diverging in arms towards the frontal angles; frontal margin transverse, smooth immediately behind; eyes completely absent; a wide antennal groove present, extending to rear of head; mentum coarsely punctate. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[435,494,1131,1150]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) 11­segmented, with a clearly 2­segmented club; basal segments sparsely and club densely setose. 
<emphasis box="[630,697,1155,1174]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[816,873,1155,1174]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) nearly parallel­sided in anterior half, indistinctly narrowed posteriorly; anterior angles directed forward; dorsally covered with large irregularly­placed tubercles, somewhat larger medially; lateral margin serrate, double when viewed laterally. Prothorax below with hypomeron slightly concave, entire ventral surface covered in slightly transverse coarse tubercles; procoxal process (
<figureCitation box="[329,385,1275,1294]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) slightly expanded behind coxae, the cavities very narrowly open behind. Elytra with distinct humeral angles; tubercles arranged in 9 indistinct rows, offset so as to give the impression of diagonal rows extending forward from the suture at 
<emphasis box="[1011,1039,1323,1342]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">ca.</emphasis>
45° angle on disc, becoming confused apically. Scutellum very small, transverse. Metathoracic wings absent. 
<emphasis box="[429,491,1371,1390]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Venter</emphasis>
: Mesosternum, metasternum and ventrites covered with unique scrollwork consisting of shining individual flat­topped tubercles and intricate interconnected sinuate lines surrounded by and surrounding flat­bottomed dull channels, the later filled with encrusted secretions; a single seta arising from each tubercle. Metasternum short, one­half the length of mesofemur; metacoxae oval, not reaching elytral margin, separated by half their width by truncate process of first ventrite. All ventrites free, with deep grooves at sutures. 
<emphasis box="[475,519,1515,1534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Legs</emphasis>
sparsely covered with setae, the tarsi 4­4­4 and unmodified, tarsomeres 1–3 subequal, and together considerably shorter than 4. 
<emphasis box="[888,1026,1539,1558]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Male genitalia</emphasis>
as in 
<figureCitation box="[246,328,1563,1582]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[269,312,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[250,1074,269,1391]" captionTargetId="figure-11@3.[243,1080,265,1401]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–4. Lyreus alleni Ivie and Ślipiński. 2) head and pronotum; 3) prosternal process; 4) male genitalia." pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Figure 4</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
